                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Ἀρχι_"><seg part="I">Ἀρχι</seg><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name></persName>
                        <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> 
                    <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Βακ_"><seg part="I"><supplied reason="lost">Β</supplied>ακ<choice><unclear>χ</unclear><unclear>υ</unclear></choice></seg><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name></persName>
                        <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2a"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
                <p>Intraduisible.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Intraducibile.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمة بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Published from a photograph found in Oliverio's archive by Pugliese Carratelli, who thought that it might be part of <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr094600</ref>.</p>
                <p>The observation of the stone shows that both thickness of the panels and lettering are quite different.</p>
	            <p>Pugliese Carratelli's idea that we might have a name in <foreign xml:lang="grc">Βακχ-</foreign> seems good, although such names are not frequent in Cyrenaica, 
	                see <bibl><ptr target="#fraser-matthews1987"/></bibl> under <foreign xml:lang="grc">Βάκχις</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="grc">Βάχις</foreign> 
	                (which are in fact feminine names <foreign xml:lang="grc">Βα(κ)χίς</foreign>).</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
